# NyayaQuest — Automated PDF Ingestion Pipeline
## Implementation Plan

---

## 1. Overview & Motivation

### The Current Problem
Every new legal PDF requires:
1. **Manual inspection** → share screenshots of PDF structure
2. **Hand-written regex** → custom `clean_text()`, `split_by_section()` per file
3. **Iterative debugging** → run → bad chunks → refine → repeat
4. **Ad-hoc edge case handling** → CPC alone has 514 lines of custom logic

### The Goal
A single command that handles any legal PDF automatically:

```bash
uv run python -m src.ingest.auto_ingest --pdf data/legal_pdfs/NewLaw_2024.pdf
```

Internal execution:
1. Intelligently filters pages (skip covers, TOC, blanks, signatures)
2. Detects if the PDF contains multiple Acts/Codes and splits accordingly
3. Analyzes the structure of each sub-document via LLM
4. Runs chunking on a pilot sample and scores the quality
5. Self-corrects the schema up to 3 times if quality is poor
6. Ingests all chunks with rich metadata into ChromaDB
7. Audits retrieval after ingest and produces a report

---

## 2. Complete Architecture

```
PDF Input
    │
    ▼
[Stage 0] Page Intelligence Filter
    │   • Classify every page (cover/toc/blank/legal/schedule/signature)
    │   • Detect and strip headers/footers (positional + pattern-based)
    │   • Handle scanned pages (detect + warn for OCR)
    │   • Handle font encoding artifacts
    │   → Output: PageManifest (page→classification map)
    │
    ▼
[Stage 1] Document Segmenter
    │   • Detect hard breaks between Acts/Codes within a single PDF
    │   • Assign page ranges and titles to each segment
    │   → Output: List[DocumentSegment]
    │
    ▼
[Stage 2] Structure Analyzer  (LLM call per segment)
    │   • Detect section/article/rule numbering patterns
    │   • Detect chapter/part heading patterns
    │   • Identify special structures (definitions, schedules, orders, tables)
    │   • Generate schema JSON
    │   → Output: SegmentSchema saved to .schema.json
    │
    ▼
[Stage 3] Pilot Chunker
    │   • Run chunker on 3 page slices (first/middle/last 5 pages) per segment
    │   → Output: PilotReport with sample chunks + metrics
    │
    ▼
[Stage 4] Quality Evaluator
    │   • Heuristic scoring (section_capture_rate, chapter_coverage, etc.)
    │   • LLM spot-check if score is borderline
    │   → PASS: proceed to Stage 6
    │   → FAIL: go to Stage 5 (up to 3 times)
    │
    ▼
[Stage 5] Schema Refiner  (LLM call, max 3x loop)
    │   • Feed bad chunk examples + failure metrics to LLM
    │   • LLM produces a schema diff (patch, not full rewrite)
    │   → Loop back to Stage 3
    │   → If 3 failures: save partial schema, print human-readable fix guide
    │
    ▼
[Stage 6] Full Ingest
    │   • Run universal chunker on all kept pages per segment
    │   • Parallel batched writes to ChromaDB
    │   → Output: Chunk IDs written to ChromaDB
    │
    ▼
[Stage 7] Post-Ingest Audit
    │   • Query ChromaDB with 1 known query per segment
    │   • Verify retrieval returns correct segment
    │   • Check chunk counts per segment are within expected range
    │   → Output: .ingest_report.json
```

---

## 3. Module File Map

```
src/ingest/
├── auto_ingest.py              # CLI entry point + pipeline orchestrator
├── page_filter.py              # Stage 0: page classification, header/footer removal
├── document_segmenter.py       # Stage 1: split multi-act PDFs into segments
├── structure_analyzer.py       # Stage 2: LLM generates schema per segment
├── schema_cache.py             # Read/write/patch .schema.json files
├── pilot_chunker.py            # Stage 3: chunking on sampled pages
├── quality_evaluator.py        # Stage 4: heuristic + LLM scoring
├── schema_refiner.py           # Stage 5: LLM patches schema on failure
├── universal_chunker.py        # Stage 6: full stateful chunker
├── ingest_to_chroma.py         # Stage 6: batched write to ChromaDB
└── post_ingest_audit.py        # Stage 7: retrieval verification
```

---

## 4. Stage-by-Stage Implementation Details

---

### Stage 0 — Page Intelligence Filter (`page_filter.py`)

#### 4.0.a Page Classification

Every page is classified into one of:

| Class | Action | Detection Signals |
|---|---|---|
| `cover` | SKIP | Text < 100 chars; likely has embedded image; no legal patterns |
| `toc` | SKIP | >40% lines have dot-leaders `......\d+`; words "Contents"/"Index" present; no paragraph text |
| `blank` | SKIP | < 20 meaningful characters |
| `gazette_header` | STRIP header, keep body | Boilerplate "GAZETTE OF INDIA" / "vlk/kkj" at fixed top position |
| `legal_content` | KEEP | Has section/article body text |
| `schedule_table` | KEEP (table mode) | Dense tabular content; likely a Schedule or Appendix |
| `signature_page` | SKIP | "By order", "Secretary to the Govt", date at end of document |
| `scanned_page` | WARN + SKIP | Very low text yield (<50 chars) despite page having content; high image content ratio |

**Classification is heuristic-only (no LLM)** — runs on every page and must be fast.

#### 4.0.b Header/Footer Detection — Two-Pass Strategy

**Pass 1 — Positional Fingerprinting (PyMuPDF block coordinates):**

```python
# Using fitz page.get_text('dict') to get block bounding boxes
# Text blocks with bbox.y0 < 8% of page height → candidate header
# Text blocks with bbox.y1 > 92% of page height → candidate footer
# Compare across 5 random pages:
#   if same text appears at same Y-position on ≥ 3 pages → universal header/footer
```

Catches static repeating text like:
- `"THE CODE ON WAGES, 2019"` (top, every page)
- `"101"` page number (bottom, every page)  
- `"Ministry of Labour & Employment"` (footer)

**Pass 2 — Legal Footnote Removal (CPC-style two-layer):**

The CPC ingest script already solved this perfectly. The universal pipeline adopts the same approach:

- **Layer 1:** Detect horizontal separator lines using `page.get_drawings()`. Any text block whose top Y-coordinate is below the separator line Y is a footnote → drop at line level (not block level — blocks can span the separator).
- **Layer 2:** For pages without a separator line, scan from the bottom upward. Lines matching `^\d{1,2}\. .*(Subs\.|Ins\.|Omitted|w\.e\.f\.|Rep\.)` are amendment footnotes → strip.

```python
# Layer 2 keyword set (exhaustive)
FOOTNOTE_KEYWORDS = [
    "Subs.", "Ins.", "Omitted", "w.e.f.", "ibid.", "A.O.", "Rep.",
    "amended in its application", "extended to .{1,40} by Act",
    "extended to the .{1,40} by", "See footnote", "vide notification"
]
```

#### 4.0.c Font Encoding Artifact Cleanup

LLM-detected PDFs will include many encoding artifacts. The pipeline applies a **universal artifact map** first, before pattern matching:

```python
ENCODING_ARTIFACT_MAP = {
    "ù":        " ",          # CPC PDF separator artifact
    "\uf0b7":   " ",          # bullet
    "\u2013":   "-",          # en-dash
    "\u2014":   "--",         # em-dash
    "\u201c":   '"',          # left smart quote
    "\u201d":   '"',          # right smart quote
    "\u2018":   "'",          # left smart single quote
    "\u2019":   "'",          # right smart single quote
    "\u00a0":   " ",          # non-breaking space
    "\u200b":   "",           # zero-width space
}

# Then apply regex for gazette-specific gibberish
GAZETTE_NOISE = r'vlk\/kkj\.k.*?CG-DL-E-\d+-\d+'  # Hindi gazette header
```

#### 4.0.d Running Headers (False Chapter Signals)

If the chapter name appears in the running header of every page (common in Indian legal PDFs), naively detecting "CHAPTER II" on every page would reset chapter state incorrectly.

**Solution:** During header fingerprinting in Pass 1, if a string that looks like a chapter heading appears at a position flagged as a header zone (top 8% of page), add it to the `header_patterns` list in the PageManifest. The Structure Analyzer and Chunker will then know to ignore those specific strings when encountered in-text.

#### 4.0.e Watermark Detection

Some PDFs embed watermark text (e.g., "DRAFT", "FOR OFFICIAL USE") as a separate transparent text layer.

**Detection:** PyMuPDF returns watermark text with very low opacity or specific rendering modes. Filter text blocks where `block['type'] == 1` (image) or where spans have `color` indicating a light grey (e.g., RGB > 0.7 for all channels).

#### 4.0.f Table / Schedule Pages

Pages containing legal tables (penalty schedules, wage rates, forms):

```python
# PyMuPDF 1.24+ find_tables() API
tables = page.find_tables()
if len(tables) > 0 and text_density(page) > 0.6:
    page_class = "schedule_table"
```

**Table chunking strategy:** Each table row becomes a chunk. The table header row is prepended to every chunk:

```
"[COW 2019] [Schedule I - Rates of Wages] 
 Header: Category | Minimum Rate | Applicability
 Row: Skilled Worker | ₹350/day | All States"
```

#### 4.0.g Scanned Page Handling

If a page yields < 50 characters despite having content (visible from page image size > 50KB), it is likely a scanned image:

```python
if len(page_text.strip()) < 50 and page.get_image_info() and page_size_kb > 50:
    page_class = "scanned_page"
```

**Action:** Log a warning, skip the page, and report in the ingest report:
```
⚠ WARNING: 3 scanned pages detected (pages 45, 46, 47). 
  These pages were skipped. Consider running OCR preprocessing 
  (tesseract / AWS Textract) if this content is critical.
```

OCR integration is out of scope for v1 but the warning points to the right tools.

#### 4.0.h Output: PageManifest

```python
@dataclass
class PageManifest:
    pdf_path: str
    total_pages: int
    page_classifications: Dict[int, str]
    header_patterns: List[str]           # text patterns to strip from all pages
    footer_patterns: List[str]
    running_header_strings: List[str]    # chapter-looking strings in header zone
    encoding_artifacts_found: List[str]  # which artifacts were detected in this PDF
    skipped_pages: List[int]
    kept_pages: List[int]
    table_pages: List[int]
    scanned_pages: List[int]
```

---

### Stage 1 — Document Segmenter (`document_segmenter.py`)

#### 4.1.a Detecting Multiple Acts in One PDF

**Hard-break signal patterns** that indicate the start of a new Act/Code:

```python
SEGMENT_BREAK_PATTERNS = [
    r'^THE [A-Z ]+(?:ACT|CODE|ORDER|RULES),\s*\d{4}',   # "THE CODE ON WAGES, 2019"
    r'^MINISTRY OF [A-Z ]+$',                              # Ministry header
    r'^No\.\s+\d+\s+of\s+\d{4}',                         # Act number
    r'^An Act to\b',                                       # Preamble start
]
```

For a compendium like the Labour Codes PDF, the segmenter would detect 4 breaks → 4 segments.

#### 4.1.b LLM Confirmation

After heuristic detection, the LLM reviews a sample of the break points:
> *"Here are 3 candidate page boundaries in a PDF. Does each boundary represent the start of a distinct Act/Code/Order? Return JSON: [{page: N, is_break: true/false, title: "...", doc_type: "act/code/order/rule"}]"*

#### 4.1.c Output: DocumentSegment List

```python
@dataclass
class DocumentSegment:
    segment_id: str           # "Labour_Codes_seg_0", "Labour_Codes_seg_1", ...
    parent_pdf: str
    doc_title: str            # "Code on Wages, 2019"
    doc_type: str             # act / code / order / notification / rules
    year: str
    page_start: int
    page_end: int
    kept_page_texts: List[str]   # filtered text for these pages
```

---

### Stage 2 — Structure Analyzer (`structure_analyzer.py`)

#### 4.2.a Sampling Strategy

For each segment, sample:
- First 5 non-TOC pages (catches numbering style, chapter format)
- 5 pages from the 40–60% range (catches main body patterns)
- Last 5 pages of the segment (catches schedules, signatures)

#### 4.2.b LLM Prompt Design

```
You are analyzing a legal document to generate a chunking schema.

Here is sample text from 3 parts of the document titled "{doc_title}":

=== BEGINNING (pages 1-5) ===
{sample_start}

=== MIDDLE (pages {mid_start}-{mid_end}) ===
{sample_middle}

=== END (pages {end_start}-{end_end}) ===
{sample_end}

Identify the following. Return ONLY valid JSON:
1. section_pattern: regex that matches section/article headings (e.g. "^\d+\.")
2. chapter_pattern: regex that matches chapter headings (e.g. "CHAPTER\s+[IVX]+")
3. part_pattern: regex for Part headings if present (or null)
4. has_definitions_section: true/false (Section 2 "definitions" pattern)
5. has_schedules: true/false
6. has_orders: true/false (like CPC Orders I-LI)
7. schedule_trigger: text that marks the start of schedules (e.g. "THE FIRST SCHEDULE")
8. order_trigger: text that marks the start of orders (or null)
9. noise_patterns: list of regex patterns for repetitive noise to strip
10. section_title_on_same_line: true/false (is section title on same line as number?)
11. numbering_style: "arabic" | "roman" | "alpha" | "mixed"
12. hierarchy: list of levels in order (e.g. ["part", "chapter", "section", "sub_section", "clause"])
13. proviso_pattern: regex for "Provided that" / "Explanation:" type sub-elements (or null)
```

#### 4.2.c Output: SegmentSchema

```python
@dataclass
class SegmentSchema:
    segment_id: str
    doc_title: str
    law_code: str
    year: str
    version: str            # "1.0", incremented by Schema Refiner
    structure_type: str     # numbered_sections / articles / orders / rules / mixed
    
    # Pattern library
    section_pattern: str
    chapter_pattern: str
    part_pattern: Optional[str]
    schedule_trigger: Optional[str]
    order_trigger: Optional[str]
    proviso_pattern: Optional[str]
    noise_patterns: List[str]
    
    # Flags
    has_definitions_section: bool
    has_schedules: bool
    has_orders: bool
    section_title_on_same_line: bool
    
    # Hierarchy
    numbering_style: str
    hierarchy: List[str]    # ["part", "chapter", "section", "sub_section", "clause"]
```

Saved to: `data/legal_pdfs/{pdf_name}.schema.json`

---

### Stage 3 — Pilot Chunker (`pilot_chunker.py`)

Runs the Universal Chunker (Stage 6 logic) on a subset of pages:

- pages[0:5] of the segment
- pages[mid-2:mid+3] of the segment  
- pages[-5:] of the segment

Returns a `PilotReport`:

```python
@dataclass
class PilotReport:
    segment_id: str
    schema_version: str
    total_pilot_chunks: int
    sample_chunks: List[dict]   # 5 representative chunks for LLM review
    metrics: dict               # raw numbers for Quality Evaluator
```

---

### Stage 4 — Quality Evaluator (`quality_evaluator.py`)

#### 4.4.a Heuristic Metrics (Layer A — no LLM, fast)

| Metric | Formula | Weight | Good Threshold |
|---|---|---|---|
| `section_capture_rate` | chunks with section_number ≠ "general" / total chunks | 30% | > 0.70 |
| `chapter_coverage` | chunks with chapter ≠ "Unknown Chapter" / total chunks | 20% | > 0.60 |
| `chunk_length_sanity` | chunks with 80 ≤ len(text) ≤ 700 chars / total chunks | 20% | > 0.75 |
| `noise_ratio` | chunks where >50% is digits/symbols / total chunks (inverted) | 20% | < 0.10 |
| `section_continuity` | are section numbers monotonically increasing? Detect big jumps | 10% | < 5 gaps |

**Overall score = weighted sum. Pass threshold = 0.70.**

Borderline zone = 0.58–0.70 → trigger Layer B.

#### 4.4.b LLM Spot Check (Layer B — used only if borderline)

Sends 5 sample chunks to LLM:
> *"Rate each chunk 1-5: (1) Is the section number correctly captured in metadata? (2) Is the text coherent and non-truncated? (3) Is there any header/footer noise present? Return JSON with scores and specific failure reasons."*

LLM score > 3.5 average → PASS with annotation. Below → FAIL.

---

### Stage 5 — Schema Refiner (`schema_refiner.py`)

**Max 3 iterations. Schema version increments each time (1.0 → 1.1 → 1.2).**

LLM prompt includes:
- Original schema JSON
- Pilot chunk samples that failed
- Specific metric that scored lowest
- Suspected root cause (auto-detected)

**Root Cause Detection Logic:**

| Failing Metric | Auto-Diagnosed Cause | Hint to LLM |
|---|---|---|
| `section_capture_rate` low | Section pattern not matching | "Check if leading whitespace or bracket `[` is needed before section numbers" |
| `noise_ratio` high | Page numbers being captured as sections | "Add page number pattern to noise_patterns" |
| `chunk_length_sanity` bad (too short) | Section split too aggressive | "Increase chunk_size or use overlap" |
| `chapter_coverage` low | Chapter heading pattern wrong | "Check Roman vs Arabic for chapter numbers" |
| `section_continuity` many gaps | Repeal markers (`[Omitted]`, `[Rep. by]`) being included | "Add omitted/repealed section filter" |

**LLM returns a JSON Patch (RFC 6902 format)** — only the changed fields:

```json
{
  "schema_version": "1.1",
  "patch": [
    {"op": "replace", "path": "/section_pattern", "value": "^\\s{0,4}(\\d+[A-Z]?)\\."},
    {"op": "add", "path": "/noise_patterns/-", "value": "^\\d{1,3}\\s*$"}
  ],
  "explanation": "Added leading whitespace tolerance; added bare page number to noise list"
}
```

**If all 3 iterations fail:**
```
⚠ INGEST ABORTED — quality threshold not met after 3 attempts

Segment: "Code on Wages, 2019"
Best score achieved: 0.58 / 0.70 threshold
Failing metric: section_capture_rate (0.28)
Suspected cause: Non-standard section numbering

→ Schema saved to: data/legal_pdfs/Labour_Codes.schema.json
→ Edit 'section_pattern' field and re-run:
   uv run python -m src.ingest.auto_ingest \
     --pdf data/legal_pdfs/Labour_Codes.pdf --use-cache
```

---

### Stage 6 — Universal Chunker (`universal_chunker.py`)

This is the core state machine that applies the schema to produce final chunks.

#### 4.6.a State Machine

```
State maintained throughout the document traversal:
    current_doc_title   : "Code on Wages, 2019"
    current_part        : "Part I — Preliminary"  
    current_chapter     : "Chapter II — Wages"
    current_section     : "3"
    current_section_title: "Wages payable on day of work"
    current_mode        : "section" | "order" | "schedule" | "table" | "preamble"
```

When the chunker encounters a **mode-switch trigger** (e.g., text matches `schedule_trigger`), it:
1. Saves all accumulated text with the current mode's metadata
2. Resets `current_chapter`, `current_section` to "Unknown"
3. Switches `current_mode` to "schedule" and applies schedule-specific patterns

#### 4.6.b Special Content Handlers

**Definitions Sections:**

Detect using `is_definition_section()`:
```python
has_clauses  = re.search(r'\(\d+\)', content)
has_quotes   = re.search(r'[""\u201c\u201d].+?[""\u201c\u201d]', content)
has_keywords = re.search(r'\b(means|includes)\b', content, re.IGNORECASE)
```

If true, extract each definition as its own chunk:
```python
# Per-definition metadata
{
    "section_type": "definition",
    "section_number": "2",        # parent section
    "sub_section": "(1)",          # clause number  
    "defined_term": "wages",       # the term being defined
    ...
}
```

**Provisos and Explanations:**

Detect inline "Provided that..." and "Explanation:" as sub-elements:
```python
PROVISO_PATTERN = r'(?:^|\n)\s*(?:Provided|Explanation|Exception|Illustration)\s*(?:that|:)'
```

Provisos are kept as part of the section chunk but flagged:
```python
"has_proviso": True,    # metadata flag
```

For very long sections with multiple provisos, each proviso is also extracted as a separate chunk with:
```python
"section_type": "proviso",
"parent_section": "3"
```

**Omitted/Repealed Sections:**

Sections marked as `[Omitted]`, `[Rep. by Act X]` should be skipped entirely:
```python
OMITTED_PATTERN = r'^\s*\[?\s*(Omitted|Repealed|Rep\.\s+by)\s*[\.\]]'
if re.match(OMITTED_PATTERN, content, re.IGNORECASE):
    continue  # skip this section
```

But a short tombstone chunk is still created for search purposes:
```python
{
    "text": "[CPC 1908] [Part III] Section 45: [Omitted by Amendment Act 1976]",
    "metadata": {"section_type": "omitted", "section_number": "45", ...}
}
```

**Section Numbering Restart Handling:**

In compendiums where Section 1 appears multiple times (once per Act), IDs are prefixed with the segment ID to avoid ChromaDB collision:

```python
chunk_id = f"{segment_id}_sec_{section_number}_{chunk_index}"
# e.g.: "Labour_Codes_seg_0_sec_1_0" vs "Labour_Codes_seg_1_sec_1_0"
```

**Amendment Inline Annotations:**

Inline amendment notes that survived footnote stripping (e.g., "Subs. by Act 36 of 2021"):
```python
INLINE_AMENDMENT_PATTERN = (
    r'\d{1,2}\.\s+(?=.*?(Subs\.|Ins\.|Omitted|w\.e\.f\.|ibid\.|'
    r'A\.O\.|Rep\.|amended in its application|extended to .{1,40} by))'
    r'[^\n]+'
)
```

These are stripped before chunking, not included in the final text.

#### 4.6.c Font/Bold Signals for Heading Detection

PyMuPDF provides font metadata per text span. Section headings are often bold:

```python
for span in line['spans']:
    is_bold = "Bold" in span['font'] or span['flags'] & 2**4  # bit 4 = bold
    is_large = span['size'] > body_font_size * 1.1
    
    if (is_bold or is_large) and matches_section_pattern(span['text']):
        # High-confidence section heading
        confidence = "high"
    else:
        confidence = "pattern_only"
```

This prevents false positives in prose text that accidentally matches a section pattern.

---

### Stage 7 — Post-Ingest Audit (`post_ingest_audit.py`)

After full ingest:

1. For each segment, query ChromaDB with 1 known query:
   - "Wage definition" for Code on Wages
   - "Right to information" for RTI
   - etc. (auto-generated by LLM from the doc_title)

2. Verify top result belongs to the correct segment (`doc_title` in metadata)

3. Check chunk count per segment is within expected range (±20% of pilot extrapolation)

4. Generate ingest report:

```json
{
    "pdf": "Labour_Codes.pdf",
    "ingested_at": "2026-04-12T08:30:00Z",
    "pipeline_version": "auto_ingest_v1",
    "segments": [
        {
            "title": "Code on Wages, 2019",
            "law_code": "COW",
            "chunks": 312,
            "quality_score": 0.87,
            "schema_version": "1.1",
            "refinement_iterations": 1,
            "retrieval_spot_check": "PASSED",
            "status": "OK"
        }
    ],
    "skipped_pages": 12,
    "scanned_pages_warned": 0,
    "overall_status": "OK"
}
```

---

## 5. Complete Metadata Schema

Every chunk written to ChromaDB uses this unified schema:

```python
{
    # ── Source tracking ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
    "source_pdf":          "Labour_Codes.pdf",
    "source_page":         47,
    "page_type":           "legal_content",
    "headers_stripped":    True,
    
    # ── Document segment info ────────────────────────────────────────────
    "parent_pdf":          "Labour_Codes.pdf",
    "doc_title":           "Code on Wages, 2019",
    "doc_type":            "code",             # act / code / order / rule / notification
    "doc_page_start":      5,
    "doc_page_end":        89,
    
    # ── Legal identity ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
    "law_code":            "COW",
    "year":                "2019",
    "structure_type":      "numbered_sections",
    
    # ── Hierarchical position ────────────────────────────────────────────
    "part":                "Part I — Preliminary",
    "chapter":             "Chapter II — Wages",
    "section_number":      "3",
    "section_title":       "Wages payable on day of work",
    "section_type":        "section",          # section / article / order / rule /
                                               # schedule_table / definition / proviso /
                                               # omitted / preamble
    "sub_section":         "(1)",
    "clause":              "(a)",
    "hierarchy_path":      "Part I > Chapter II > Section 3 > (1)(a)",
    
    # ── Special fields for definitions ───────────────────────────────────
    "defined_term":        "wages",            # only for section_type == "definition"
    
    # ── Special fields for schedules/orders ──────────────────────────────
    "order":               null,               # "I", "II", etc. for CPC-style orders
    "order_title":         null,
    "rule":                null,               # rule number within an order
    "schedule_name":       null,               # "Schedule I — Rates of Wages"
    "table_row":           null,               # row index within a table chunk
    
    # ── Chunk positioning ────────────────────────────────────────────────
    "chunk_index":         2,
    "total_chunks":        4,
    "chunk_char_length":   312,
    "has_proviso":         False,
    "boundary":            False,              # True if chunk is at a section boundary
    
    # ── Pipeline provenance ──────────────────────────────────────────────
    "schema_version":      "1.1",
    "quality_score":       0.87,
    "ingested_at":         "2026-04-12T08:30:00Z",
    "pipeline_version":    "auto_ingest_v1",
}
```

---

## 6. Edge Case Inventory

All edge cases handled by this pipeline:

| Edge Case | Handled By | Strategy |
|---|---|---|
| Multi-Act PDF | Stage 1 Segmenter | Hard-break detection + LLM confirmation |
| Mixed section patterns (Section + Article + Order) | Stage 2 Schema: `structure_type: "mixed"` | Mode-switch in state machine |
| Schedules with different numbering | Stage 6: `schedule_trigger` + mode switch | Separate chunking strategy for `current_mode == "schedule"` |
| CPC-style Orders (Order I–LI) with Rules | Stage 6: `order_trigger` + order/rule extraction | Nested order→rule hierarchy |
| Table-heavy Schedule pages | Stage 0: `schedule_table` classification | PyMuPDF `find_tables()` API |
| Table of Contents pages | Stage 0: `toc` classification | Skipped entirely |
| Cover / logo-only pages | Stage 0: `cover` classification | Skipped |
| Signature/closing pages | Stage 0: `signature_page` classification | Skipped |
| Blank pages | Stage 0: `blank` classification | Skipped |
| Scanned/image-only pages | Stage 0: `scanned_page` detection | Skipped + warning |
| Running headers (false chapter signals) | Stage 0: recorded in `running_header_strings` | Stage 6 ignores these strings when in header zone |
| Static headers/footers | Stage 0: positional fingerprinting | Stripped universally |
| Legal footnote annotations | Stage 0: two-layer (separator line + keyword scan) | Stripped before chunking |
| Inline amendment annotations | Stage 6: `INLINE_AMENDMENT_PATTERN` | Stripped from content text |
| Watermark text | Stage 0: opacity/color filter | Filtered from text extraction |
| Font encoding artifacts | Stage 0: `ENCODING_ARTIFACT_MAP` | Normalized before any pattern matching |
| Hindi/Devanagari gazette gibberish | Stage 0: `GAZETTE_NOISE` regex | Stripped |
| Repealed/omitted sections | Stage 6: `OMITTED_PATTERN` | Skipped, tombstone chunk created |
| Section numbering restart (compendium) | Stage 6: segment-prefixed IDs | `{segment_id}_sec_{n}` format |
| Definition sections with sub-clauses | Stage 6: `is_definition_section()` + `extract_definitions()` | Each definition = 1 chunk, `defined_term` in metadata |
| Provisos and Explanations | Stage 6: `proviso_pattern` | Flagged in metadata; extracted as separate chunks if long |
| Bold/font-size heading signals | Stage 6: span font flags | Used as confirmation signal alongside regex |
| Very long sections with many sub-clauses | Stage 6: `RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter` | Splits on `["\n\n", "\n", " ", ""]` with overlap |
| Preamble ("WHEREAS...") | Stage 6: pre-section detection | `section_type: "preamble"`, `section_number: "preamble"` |
| Section title on same line vs next line | Stage 2 Schema: `section_title_on_same_line` flag | Extraction logic branched |
| Non-sequential section numbers | Stage 4 Quality Evaluator | `section_continuity` metric detects big gaps |
| Poor schema on first attempt | Stage 5 Schema Refiner | Max 3 self-correction iterations |
| Permanent failure after 3 attempts | Stage 5 fallback | Human-readable fix guide + partial schema saved |

---

## 7. CLI Reference

```bash
# Standard usage (full pipeline)
uv run python -m src.ingest.auto_ingest --pdf data/legal_pdfs/NewLaw.pdf

# Re-ingest using cached schema (no LLM re-analysis)
uv run python -m src.ingest.auto_ingest --pdf data/legal_pdfs/NewLaw.pdf --use-cache

# Force re-analysis (if PDF has been updated)
uv run python -m src.ingest.auto_ingest --pdf data/legal_pdfs/NewLaw.pdf --reanalyze

# Dry run: analyze and show sample chunks, don't write to ChromaDB
uv run python -m src.ingest.auto_ingest --pdf data/legal_pdfs/NewLaw.pdf --dry-run

# Override law_code
uv run python -m src.ingest.auto_ingest --pdf data/legal_pdfs/NewLaw.pdf --law-code NL

# Skip post-ingest audit (faster, use when iterating)
uv run python -m src.ingest.auto_ingest --pdf data/legal_pdfs/NewLaw.pdf --no-audit
```

---

## 8. Files Created Per PDF

```
data/legal_pdfs/
├── Labour_Codes.pdf                  # original PDF (unchanged)
├── Labour_Codes.schema.json          # generated/cached schema for all segments
├── Labour_Codes.page_manifest.json   # page classification results
└── Labour_Codes.ingest_report.json   # post-ingest audit results
```

---

## 9. Implementation Order

1. `page_filter.py` — everything depends on clean page text
2. `document_segmenter.py` — segmentation before schema generation
3. `structure_analyzer.py` + `schema_cache.py` — LLM schema generation
4. `universal_chunker.py` — core chunking logic (most complex)
5. `pilot_chunker.py` — thin wrapper around universal_chunker for sampling
6. `quality_evaluator.py` — scoring logic
7. `schema_refiner.py` — LLM patch generation
8. `ingest_to_chroma.py` — ChromaDB write (reuse existing logic)
9. `post_ingest_audit.py` — retrieval verification
10. `auto_ingest.py` — CLI orchestrator tying all stages together
